new='PASSAGES["Level 21"]=[{title:"The Hidden Economics of Social Media Influencers",text:"The influencer economy, now valued in the tens of billions of dollars globally, operates on financial mechanics that remain largely invisible to the average follower scrolling through a feed. Brands have increasingly shifted advertising budgets away from traditional channels like television toward influencer partnerships, driven by research suggesting that audiences trust recommendations from creators they feel a personal connection with far more than conventional advertisements. This has created an entire infrastructure of talent agencies, analytics platforms, and contract negotiators that did not exist a decade ago, all dedicated to quantifying something once considered unquantifiable: authentic trust. Influencers are now evaluated using detailed metrics including engagement rate, audience demographics, and even sentiment analysis of comment sections, with smaller creators who have devoted niche followings sometimes commanding higher fees per follower than celebrities with massive but less engaged audiences, a phenomenon that has surprised traditional marketers. Regulatory bodies in multiple countries have struggled to keep pace with this rapidly evolving industry, introducing disclosure requirements for sponsored content only after significant public pressure, while critics argue that the blurred line between genuine recommendation and paid promotion fundamentally undermines the authenticity that made influencer marketing effective in the first place, creating a tension at the very core of the business model.",qs:["Why have brands shifted advertising budgets toward influencers according to the passage?","What does the passage suggest about how influencer value is measured?","What tension does the passage identify at the core of influencer marketing?","Do you think sponsored content should always be clearly labeled? Why or why not?"]},{title:"The Paradox of Choice in Modern Life",text:"Psychologist Barry Schwartz popularized an idea that initially seems counterintuitive: that having more options to choose from can decrease rather than increase a person\'s satisfaction and wellbeing, a phenomenon now widely referred to as the paradox of choice. Experimental research lends considerable support to this idea. In one frequently cited study, customers offered a smaller selection of jam flavours at a tasting table were significantly more likely to actually make a purchase than those offered a much larger selection, despite expressing greater initial interest in the larger display. Researchers propose that an overwhelming number of options increases the cognitive effort required to make a decision, increases the likelihood of regret afterward, since any chosen option inevitably means forgoing potential benefits of all alternatives, and increases anxiety about whether the best possible choice was truly made. This effect appears to apply across remarkably diverse contexts, from selecting a streaming show to choosing a university or career path. Some economists studying digital platforms have begun designing interfaces specifically intended to reduce excessive choice, curating smaller, more manageable selections, while critics counter that limiting options paternalistically assumes people cannot be trusted to navigate complexity on their own, representing a fundamental disagreement about human autonomy.",qs:["What is the paradox of choice, and what did the jam study demonstrate?","What three reasons does the passage give for why more choices can decrease satisfaction?","How have some companies responded to this research?","Can you think of a time when too many options made a decision harder for you?"]},{title:"How Cities Are Designed to Shape Behaviour",text:"Urban planners have long understood that the physical design of a city does far more than simply provide infrastructure; it actively shapes how people behave, interact, and even feel on a daily basis, often in ways residents never consciously notice. Streets intentionally narrowed and lined with shops encourage pedestrians to walk slowly and linger, increasing local commerce, while wide highways through urban centres tend to discourage walking entirely and can fragment neighbourhoods and communities, a pattern many cities are now working to reverse decades later. Researchers studying urban design have found that the presence of visible greenery, such as street trees and small parks, correlates with measurably lower reported stress levels among residents, even when controlling for income and other socioeconomic factors. Lighting design similarly influences perceived safety, with poorly lit areas increasing fear of crime independent of actual crime statistics in that location. Some cities have begun deliberately applying psychological research to public design, an approach sometimes called behavioural urbanism, using strategically placed benches to encourage social interaction among strangers, or curved pathways through parks specifically engineered to slow walking pace and encourage relaxation. Critics of this approach raise concerns about who ultimately decides which behaviours should be encouraged and whose specific cultural notion of an ideal public life is being designed into the urban environment.",qs:["How does street design influence pedestrian behaviour according to the passage?","What did researchers find about greenery and stress levels?","What is behavioural urbanism, and what is one example given in the passage?","What concern do critics raise about deliberately designing cities to shape behaviour?"]}];\n'
